    "## Visualizations\n",
    "\n",
    "- scatter plots\n",
    "- correlation matrices\n",
    "    - correlation only captures linear relationships. For our project, we might need combination of feartures as the network attacks might not be detected by one simple feature.\n",
    "- bar charts\n",
    "- line graph, etc."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a3d9608c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The correlation matrix shows that most numeric predictors have weak linear correlations with the dependent variable `label`. The strongest correlation is `dns_qtype` with approximately -0.26, followed by `src_port` with approximately 0.23, `dst_port` with approximately -0.16, `dns_qclass` with approximately -0.15, and `src_pkts` with approximately -0.10. Although these correlations are not very strong, they suggest that DNS-related features, port numbers, and packet counts may be useful for distinguishing normal traffic from attack traffic. Since the correlations are generally weak, the final model may need to rely on combinations of features rather than one individual predictor.\n",
    "\n",
    "Some predictors are strongly correlated with each other. For example, `src_pkts` and `src_ip_bytes` have a strong positive correlation around 0.88, which makes sense because more source packets usually means more source IP bytes. Similarly, `src_bytes` and `dst_bytes` are moderately correlated. These relationships may be useful to consider during feature selection because highly correlated predictors can sometimes provide overlapping information."
   ]
  },
